>
  <p>
    The way of the point is a path traced through the chart, from the Judge back through the
    Witnesses and Nieces to the top row, by following the figures' top lines. It shows the
    underlying place of a matter and serves as a late check on a reading, after the houses, the
    triad, and perfection.
  </p>

  <h2>Find the way of the point</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Take the top line of the Judge, whether it has one point or two.</li>
    <li>Compare the top lines of the two Witnesses. The way runs toward the Witness whose top line matches the Judge. If neither matches, there is no way of the point; record that and stop.</li>
    <li>Follow the matching top line up into the Nieces (houses nine to twelve), keeping to the house whose top line still matches the Judge.</li>
    <li>Follow the match up once more into the top row by the same rule: the ninth house leads to the first and second, the tenth to the third and fourth, the eleventh to the fifth and sixth, the twelfth to the seventh and eighth.</li>
    <li>Read the figure where the way ends, by its nature and its house. A good figure gives a good finding, an ill figure an ill one.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    A single point on the Judge's top line always threads the way to one figure; a double top makes
    it fork or fail. A recorded "no way of the point" is itself a finding.
  </p>

  <h2>In the sources</h2>
  <p>Cattan counts it among the most necessary rules of the art:</p>
